{"title_page": "Edem Kodjo", "text_new": "{{short description|Togolese politician and former Prime Minister}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Edem Kodjo\n|image       = Edem Kodjo-Festival international de g\u00e9ographie 2011.jpg\n|order       = 4th\n|office      = Secretary-General of the Organisation of African Unity\n|term_start  = July 21, 1978\n|term_end    = June 12, 1983\n|predecessor = [[William Eteki]]\n|successor   = Peter Onu\n|office2      = 3rd [[List of heads of government of Togo|Prime Minister of Togo]]\n|president2   = [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]]\n|term_start2  = April 23, 1994\n|term_end2    = August 20, 1996\n|predecessor2 = [[Joseph Kokou Koffigoh]]\n|successor2   = [[Kwassi Klutse]]\n|office3      =\n|president3   = [[Faure Gnassingb\u00e9]]\n|term_start3  = June 9, 2005\n|term_end3    = September 20, 2006\n|predecessor3 = [[Koffi Sama]]\n|successor3   = [[Yawovi Agboyibo]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1938|5|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Sokod\u00e9]], [[Tchaoudjo]], [[French Togoland]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|4|11|1938|5|23}}\n|death_place = [[Paris]], France\n|nationality = Togolese\n|profession  = Administrator, teacher, writer, publisher\n}}\n'''\u00c9douard Kodjovi \"Edem\" Kodjo''' (May 23, 1938 \u2013 April 11, 2020), was a [[Togo]]lese politician and diplomat. He was Secretary-General of the [[Organisation of African Unity]] from 1978 to 1983; later, in Togo, he was a prominent opposition leader after the introduction of multi-party politics. He served as [[Prime Minister of Togo|Prime Minister]] from 1994 to 1996 and again from 2005 to 2006. Kodjo was President of the [[Patriotic Pan-African Convergence]] (CPP).<ref>[http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?d=3&i=113&o=1&s=373 \"Une d\u00e9mocratie en bonne sant\u00e9\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613173912/http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?o=1&s=373&d=3&i=113 |date=June 13, 2008 }}, Republicoftogo.com, January 12, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo died on April 11, 2020, in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicoftogo.com/Toutes-les-rubriques/Politique/Au-revoir-Edouard|title=Au revoir Edouard|date=May 11, 2020|website=R\u00e9publique Togolaise|language=fr|url-status=live|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKodjo was born in [[Sokod\u00e9]], [[Tchaoudjo|Tchaoudjo Prefecture]], [[French Togoland]] on May 23, 1938.<ref name=CENI>[http://www.cenitogo.tg/listecandidats/AVE.pdf List of candidates in Av\u00e9 Prefecture in the 2007 election] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911142405/http://www.cenitogo.tg/listecandidats/AVE.pdf |date=September 11, 2008 }}, CENI website {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Profil>[http://www.icilome.com/nouvelles/news.asp?id=83&idnews=1906&f= \"Pr\u00e9sidentielles 2003 : Profil des candidats\"], iciLome.com, May 16, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> He had his secondary school education at West Africa Secondary School in Ghana.<ref name=CENI/><ref name=Profil/>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nAfter completing his studies in France, he was an administrator at the ''[[Office de Radiodiffusion T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Fran\u00e7aise]]''<ref name=Profil/> from November 1964 to June 1967. He then returned to Togo and was appointed by President [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]] as Secretary-General of the Ministry of Finance in July 1967.<ref name=Visage>[http://www.diastode.org/Echos/invit5629.html \"EDEM KODJO \u00c0 VISAGE D\u00c9COUVERT\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217112243/http://www.diastode.org/Echos/invit5629.html |date=February 17, 2005 }}, diastode.org {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo participated in the creation of the [[Rally of the Togolese People]] (RPT) ruling party in late 1969 and became the new party's Secretary-General.<ref name=Profil/><ref name=Visage/> He also wrote the \"Green Book\", which served as the ideological basis for the establishment of the RPT's single-party rule.<ref name=CDD>Morten Hagen and Michelle Spearing, [http://www.diastode.org/Droits/cdd.html \"TOGO \u2013 STALLED DEMOCRATIC TRANSITION\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902023414/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/cdd.html |date=September 2, 2012 }}, Centre for Democracy & Development, November 28, 2000.</ref> He was removed from his position as RPT Secretary-General in 1971.<ref name=Profil/>\n\nKodjo served in Eyad\u00e9ma's government as [[Minister of Finance (Togo)|Minister of Finance]] from 1973 to 1977,<ref>[https://finances.gouv.tg/node/98 Historique du minist\u00e8re | Minist\u00e8re de l'Economie et des Finances]</ref> and as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Togo)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1976 to 1978.<ref name=Profil/> He was elected as the Secretary-General of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) at its summit in [[Khartoum]] on July 18\u201322, 1978.<ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/Fichiers/MFI/PolitiqueDiplomatie/575.asp \"Sommet de l\u2019Union africaine \u2013 Durban 2002 (5) : L\u2019OUA, quarante ans d'histoire\u2026\"], rfi.fr, May 16, 2002 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> One of the key issues facing the OAU during Kodjo's five-year tenure was the status of the [[Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic]] (SADR), which claimed independence for the former colony of [[Spanish Sahara]], at that time partly occupied by Morocco. Kodjo controversially allowed the SADR to be seated as a member of the OAU on February 28, 1982, over the objections of Morocco and various other African countries that supported the Moroccan position. According to Kodjo, that decision was based simply on the fact that a majority of OAU member states had recognized the SADR, but it led to a serious crisis within the OAU, with a number of member states boycotting OAU meetings.<ref>Stefan Talmon, ''Recognition of Governments in International Law'' (1998), Oxford University Press, page 187.</ref> [[Senegal]]ese President [[Abdou Diouf]] accused Kodjo of \"mischief-making\".<ref>Omar A. Touray, ''The Gambia and the World: A History of the Foreign Policy of Africa's Smallest State, 1965\u20131995'' (2000), page 151.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving his post as OAU Secretary-General in 1983,<ref name=Fief>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/togo/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=XIN70027togolfeifno0 \"Togo/l\u00e9gislatives: l'ex-Premier ministre Kodjo candidat dans son fief\"], Xinhua (Jeuneafrique.com), August 12, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo lived in France, where he taught at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], wrote for ''[[Jeune Afrique]]'', and founded a magazine, ''Afrique 2000''.<ref name=Demo>[http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete6c.html \"D\u00c9MOCRATISATION \u00c0 LA TOGOLAISE\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106144111/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete6c.html |date=January 6, 2009 }} (\"L\u2019\u00e9narque et le \u00abparti croupion\u00bb\"), T\u00e8t\u00e8 T\u00e9t\u00e9, 1998 (diastode.org) {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> In 1985 he published ''[[Africa Tomorrow]]'' in France, which was later translated into English by [[E. B. Khan]] and published in the United States in 1987.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Marien|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5FQVtSVI3JEC&pg=PA32|title=Future Survey Annual 1987: A Guide to the Recent Literature of Trends, Forecasts, and Policy Proposals|date=January 1, 1988|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-930242-34-3|pages=32|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====1990s====\nIn 1991, a few months before the National Conference, Kodjo returned to Togo and founded a new opposition political party, the [[Togolese Union for Democracy]] (UTD).<ref name=Demo/> On July 20, 1993,<ref name=Chron>[http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete_chro.html \"D\u00e9mocratisation \u00e0 la Togolaise\"], T\u00e8t\u00e8 T\u00e9t\u00e9, 1998 {{in lang|fr}}. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217151407/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete_chro.html |date=December 17, 2008 }}</ref> he was designated by the [[Collective of Democratic Opposition]] (COD II) as its sole candidate for the [[1993 Togolese presidential election|presidential election]] of August 25, 1993,<ref name=Profil/><ref name=Chron/><ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/1993-07-22_Articles_-ITALIE \"Togo. Le collectif de l\u2019opposition\"], ''L'Humanit\u00e9'', July 22, 1993 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> although [[Gilchrist Olympio]] of the [[Union of the Forces of Change]] (UFC) did not accept this decision.<ref name=Chron/> Along with fellow opposition leaders [[Yawovi Agboyibo]] and [[Djobo Boukari]], Kodjo announced on August 22 that he was withdrawing his candidacy and boycotting the election due to the number of registered voters being considered too high\u2014a possible sign of preparations to rig the election.<ref>John R. Heilbrunn, \"Togo: The National Conference and Stalled Reform\", in ''Political Reform in Francophone Africa'' (1997), ed. John F. Clark and David E. Gardinier, page 240.</ref>\n\nAlong with other opposition leaders, Kodjo pressured Eyad\u00e9ma to hold a free and fair [[1994 Togolese parliamentary election|parliamentary election in 1994]]. In this election, the [[Action Committee for Renewal]] (CAR) and the UTD together won an initial majority in the [[National Assembly of Togo|National Assembly]],<ref name=South>''Africa South of the Sahara 2004'' (2003), Routledge, page 1,145.</ref><ref name=Named>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE7D61131F937A15757C0A962958260 \"Togo Premier Named\"], ''The New York Times'', April 24, 1994.</ref> the CAR with 36 seats and the UTD with seven;<ref name=Named/> Kodjo himself won a seat from [[Lom\u00e9]].<ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/topic,463af2212,469f2f522,469f38e9c,0.html \"Chronology for Kabre in Togo\"], Minorities at Risk Project, 2004.</ref> The CAR and UTD initially agreed to nominate CAR President Yawovi Agboyibo as Prime Minister. However, after the election in three constituencies was cancelled, the two parties lost their narrow majority, and Eyad\u00e9ma invited Kodjo to form a government,<ref name=South/> announcing his appointment as Prime Minister on April 22, 1994;<ref name=Chron/><ref name=Named/> he took office on April 25.<ref name=Chron/> The CAR regarded Kodjo's appointment as a violation of the parties' agreement and refused to participate in his government.<ref name=\"South\"/> His acceptance of the position of Prime Minister, in addition to his earlier role in the establishment of the RPT regime, discredited him in the eyes of many opposition supporters.<ref name=CDD/> His government was announced on May 25, 1994; it included the RPT, the UTD, and some smaller parties not represented in the National Assembly. Although headed by Kodjo, the composition of the government was strongly dominated by the RPT.<ref>\"May 1994 \u2013 New government\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', volume 40, May 1994, Togo, page 39,995.</ref>\n\nKodjo served as Prime Minister of Togo until August 20, 1996. He resigned as Prime Minister after the RPT won the elections that were held over again in the constituencies where the results had been annulled, giving the RPT and its allies a parliamentary majority; a new government under [[Kwassi Klutse]] of the RPT was formed.<ref name=South/>\n\nOn the night of August 13, 1997, [[tear gas]] canisters were thrown at Kodjo's house while he was exiting it with guests. The UTD alleged that the canisters were thrown from a police vehicle.<ref>[http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Newsletters/irinw30.html \"Togo \u2013 Opposition members attacked\"], IRIN-WA Daily Media Update 30\u201397, August 15, 1997.</ref> Kodjo announced on May 4, 1998 that he would not be a candidate in the [[1998 Togolese presidential election|June 1998 presidential election]], stressing the need for opposition unity.<ref>[http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Newsletters/irinw200.html \"Togo: Call for one opposition candidate\"], IRIN-West Africa Update 200, May 5, 1998.</ref> He backed the leading opposition candidate, UFC President Gilchrist Olympio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/OUEST/togo/togopartis/partisoppositiontogo.htm|title=Partis politiques d'opposition du Togo|work=Afrique Express|language=fr|access-date=April 13, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060205164351/http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/OUEST/togo/togopartis/partisoppositiontogo.htm|archive-date=February 5, 2006}}</ref>\n\n====2000\u20132020====\n\nKodjo subsequently became the leader of a new party, the Patriotic Pan-African Convergence (CPP), which was created in August 1999<ref name=Briefing>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=980CE1DD1E39F934A2575BC0A96F958260 \"Togo: Opposition alliance\"], ''The New York Times'', August 17, 1999.</ref> through the merger of four parties,<ref name=Briefing/><ref name=PP>''Political Parties of the World'' (6th edition, 2005), ed. Bogdan Szajkowski, page 591.</ref> including the UTD.<ref name=PP/> Kodjo ran as the CPP's candidate in the [[2003 Togolese presidential election|June 2003 presidential election]].<ref name=PP/><ref name=Security>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=44013 \"Togo: Security {{sic|person|el|hide=y}}<!-- PLEASE NOTE that \"personel\" is deliberately spelled incorrectly here, reflecting the mistake on the external page. --> to vote on Thursday instead of Sunday\"], IRIN, May 28, 2003.</ref> Kodjo criticized Eyad\u00e9ma for not honoring his pledge to step down in the 2003 election and again called for the opposition to put forward a single candidate.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=43633 \"Togo: Constitutional Court upholds Olympio's rejection\"], IRIN, May 7, 2003.</ref> During the campaign, the CPP called for a debate on television between Kodjo and Eyad\u00e9ma after the RPT engaged in what the CPP considered personal attacks on Kodjo.<ref name=Security/> In the election, Kodjo received 0.96% of the vote according to official results<ref name=Dem>[http://democratie.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/TOGO_RME24042005.pdf \"RAPPORT DE LA MISSION EXPLORATOIRE DEPECHEE DANS LA PERSPECTIVE DE L\u2019ELECTION PRESIDENTIELLE ANTICIPEE DU 24 AVRIL 2005 AU TOGO\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070622094405/http://democratie.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/TOGO_RME24042005.pdf |date=June 22, 2007 }}, democratie.francophonie.org {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Sans>[http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/066/article_36733.asp \"Edem Kodjo, un Premier ministre sans transition\"], Radio France Internationale, June 9, 2005 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> and took fifth place;<ref name=Dem/> he denounced the results as fraudulent.<ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/2003-06-05_International_-Zoom-Togo \"La transparence n\u2019est pas au rendez-vous\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513220431/http://www.humanite.fr/2003-06-05_International_-Zoom-Togo |date=May 13, 2008 }}, ''L'Humanit\u00e9'', June 5, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nFollowing the disputed [[2005 Togolese presidential election|April 2005 presidential election]], which occurred shortly after Eyadema's death, Eyadema's son and successor [[Faure Gnassingb\u00e9]] named Kodjo, a representative of the moderate opposition, as Prime Minister again on June 8, 2005, choosing him instead of a candidate from the radical opposition.<ref name=Sans/><ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=47579&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=TOGO \"President snubs opponents for 'moderate' prime minister\"], IRIN, June 9, 2005.</ref> He took office on June 9, succeeding [[Koffi Sama]].<ref>\"Former Togolese premier hands over to successor, Edem Kodjo \u2013 radio report\", Radio Togo, June 10, 2005.</ref>\n\nIn an announcement on September 16, 2006, Gnassingb\u00e9 accepted Kodjo's resignation and named [[Yawovi Agboyibo]] as Prime Minister.<ref>Ebow Godwin, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2006/09/16/international/i150128D70.DTL&type=politics \"Togo's President Names Opposition Party\"], Associated Press, September 16, 2006.</ref> On September 25, Gnassingb\u00e9 appointed Kodjo by decree as Minister of State to the Presidency.<ref>[http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=655 \"Togo : Edem Kodjo coopt\u00e9 ministre d\u2019Etat dans le gouvernement Agboyibo\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022161714/http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=655 |date=October 22, 2006 }}, Infosplusgabon.com, September 26, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2007 Togolese parliamentary election|October 2007 parliamentary election]], Kodjo ran for a seat in the [[National Assembly of Togo|National Assembly]] as a candidate of the CPP in [[Av\u00e9, Togo|Av\u00e9 Prefecture]], where he was the first name on the party's candidate list.<ref name=CENI/><ref name=Fief/> The CPP did not win any seats in the election.<ref name=Results>Text of Constitutional Court decision (final election results), October 30, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}. {{cite web |url=http://www.cenitogo.tg/resultats/Resultats_definitifs_des_elections_legislatives_du_14_octobre_2007_%20proclames_par_la_Cour_Constitutionnelle.do.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129155756/http://www.cenitogo.tg/resultats/Resultats_definitifs_des_elections_legislatives_du_14_octobre_2007_%20proclames_par_la_Cour_Constitutionnelle.do.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2007  }}</ref>\n\nAt a CPP congress in late April 2009, Kodjo announced that he was retiring from day-to-day politics in order to make way for younger leadership. He also said that he would not be a candidate in the [[2010 Togolese presidential election|2010 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?o=5&s=1&d=3&i=3663 \"Edem Kodjo prend de la distance\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Republicoftogo.com, April 26, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Acting as the Special Envoy of [[La Francophonie]], he arrived in [[Madagascar]] to help [[Malagasy political crisis, 2009|mediate in that country's political crisis]] on May 8, 2009.<ref>Iloniaina Alain, [http://www.lexpressmada.com/display.php?p=display&id=26394 \"Les \u00e9missaires francophones rassurent\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022102459/http://www.lexpressmada.com/display.php?p=display |date=October 22, 2007 }}, ''L'Express de Madagascar'', May 13, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> In an interview with ''Jeune Afrique'', published in May 2009, he said that he had served his country in all possible capacities, except that of President: \"I have made my contribution to the construction of my country\". According to Kodjo, he had lost interest in \"internal politics\" and preferred to devote himself to Pan-Africanism by working to facilitate a cooperative approach to finding solutions to African problems.<ref>Tshitenge Lubabu, [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2523p032-033.xml0/-Edem-Kodjo-retraite-portrait-La-quatrieme-vie-d-Edem-Kodjo.html \"La quatri\u00e8me vie d'Edem Kodjo\"], ''Jeune Afrique'', May 26, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he acted as the African Union's mediator during the dispute between the government and the opposition in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] regarding the timing of the next election.<ref>Aaron Ross, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-congo-politics-idUSKCN10V0I5?il=0 \"Congo opposition rejects talks with Kabila government over election\"], Reuters, August 20, 2016.</ref>\n\nKodjo died of an unspecified long illness on April 11, 2020, in [[Paris]], France. The Togolese Foreign Minister [[Robert Dussey]] paid tribute to him, calling him \"a brilliant academic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/04/12/edem-kodjo-togo-mourns-ex-prime-minister-africa-remembers-ex-oau-chief//|title=Edem Kodjo: Togo mourns ex-Prime Minister, Africa remembers ex-OAU chief|last=Shaban|first=Abdur Rahman|date=|website=AfricaNews|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Togo]]|before=[[Joseph Kokou Koffigoh]]|after=[[Kwassi Klutse]]|years=1994\u20131996}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Togo]]|before=[[Koffi Sama]]|after=[[Yawovi Agboyibo]]|years=2005\u20132006}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TogolesePMs}}\n{{African Union Commission chairpersons}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kodjo, Edem}}\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:University of Paris faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Togo)]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole nationale d'administration alumni]]\n[[Category:Patriotic Pan-African Convergence politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Sokod\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Togolese politician and former Prime Minister}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Edem Kodjo\n|image       = Edem Kodjo-Festival international de g\u00e9ographie 2011.jpg\n|order       = 4th\n|office      = Secretary-General of the Organisation of African Unity\n|term_start  = July 21, 1978\n|term_end    = June 12, 1983\n|predecessor = [[William Eteki]]\n|successor   = Peter Onu\n|office2      = 3rd [[List of heads of government of Togo|Prime Minister of Togo]]\n|president2   = [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]]\n|term_start2  = April 23, 1994\n|term_end2    = August 20, 1996\n|predecessor2 = [[Joseph Kokou Koffigoh]]\n|successor2   = [[Kwassi Klutse]]\n|office3      =\n|president3   = [[Faure Gnassingb\u00e9]]\n|term_start3  = June 9, 2005\n|term_end3    = September 20, 2006\n|predecessor3 = [[Koffi Sama]]\n|successor3   = [[Yawovi Agboyibo]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1938|5|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Sokod\u00e9]], [[Tchaoudjo]], [[French Togoland]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|4|11|1938|5|23}}\n|death_place = [[Paris]], France\n|nationality = Togolese\n|profession  = Administrator, teacher, writer, publisher\n}}\n'''\u00c9douard Kodjovi \"Edem\" Kodjo''' (May 23, 1938 \u2013 April 11, 2020), was a [[Togo]]lese politician and diplomat. He was Secretary-General of the [[Organisation of African Unity]] from 1978 to 1983; later, in Togo, he was a prominent opposition leader after the introduction of multi-party politics. He served as [[Prime Minister of Togo|Prime Minister]] from 1994 to 1996 and again from 2005 to 2006. Kodjo was President of the [[Patriotic Pan-African Convergence]] (CPP).<ref>[http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?d=3&i=113&o=1&s=373 \"Une d\u00e9mocratie en bonne sant\u00e9\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613173912/http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?o=1&s=373&d=3&i=113 |date=June 13, 2008 }}, Republicoftogo.com, January 12, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo died on April 11, 2020, in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicoftogo.com/Toutes-les-rubriques/Politique/Au-revoir-Edouard|title=Au revoir Edouard|date=May 11, 2020|website=R\u00e9publique Togolaise|language=fr|url-status=live|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKodjo was born in [[Sokod\u00e9]], [[Tchaoudjo|Tchaoudjo Prefecture]], [[French Togoland]] on May 23, 1938.<ref name=CENI>[http://www.cenitogo.tg/listecandidats/AVE.pdf List of candidates in Av\u00e9 Prefecture in the 2007 election] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911142405/http://www.cenitogo.tg/listecandidats/AVE.pdf |date=September 11, 2008 }}, CENI website {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Profil>[http://www.icilome.com/nouvelles/news.asp?id=83&idnews=1906&f= \"Pr\u00e9sidentielles 2003 : Profil des candidats\"], iciLome.com, May 16, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> He had his secondary school education at West Africa Secondary School in Ghana.<ref name=CENI/><ref name=Profil/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter completing his studies in France, he was an administrator at the ''[[Office de Radiodiffusion T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Fran\u00e7aise]]''<ref name=Profil/> from November 1964 to June 1967. He then returned to Togo and was appointed by President [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]] as Secretary-General of the Ministry of Finance in July 1967.<ref name=Visage>[http://www.diastode.org/Echos/invit5629.html \"EDEM KODJO \u00c0 VISAGE D\u00c9COUVERT\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050217112243/http://www.diastode.org/Echos/invit5629.html |date=February 17, 2005 }}, diastode.org {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo participated in the creation of the [[Rally of the Togolese People]] (RPT) ruling party in late 1969 and became the new party's Secretary-General.<ref name=Profil/><ref name=Visage/> He also wrote the \"Green Book\", which served as the ideological basis for the establishment of the RPT's single-party rule.<ref name=CDD>Morten Hagen and Michelle Spearing, [http://www.diastode.org/Droits/cdd.html \"TOGO \u2013 STALLED DEMOCRATIC TRANSITION\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902023414/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/cdd.html |date=September 2, 2012 }}, Centre for Democracy & Development, November 28, 2000.</ref> He was removed from his position as RPT Secretary-General in 1971.<ref name=Profil/>\n\nKodjo served in Eyad\u00e9ma's government as [[Minister of Finance (Togo)|Minister of Finance]] from 1973 to 1977,<ref>[https://finances.gouv.tg/node/98 Historique du minist\u00e8re | Minist\u00e8re de l'Economie et des Finances]</ref> and as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Togo)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1976 to 1978.<ref name=Profil/> He was elected as the Secretary-General of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) at its summit in [[Khartoum]] on July 18\u201322, 1978.<ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/Fichiers/MFI/PolitiqueDiplomatie/575.asp \"Sommet de l\u2019Union africaine \u2013 Durban 2002 (5) : L\u2019OUA, quarante ans d'histoire\u2026\"], rfi.fr, May 16, 2002 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> One of the key issues facing the OAU during Kodjo's five-year tenure was the status of the [[Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic]] (SADR), which claimed independence for the former colony of [[Spanish Sahara]], at that time partly occupied by Morocco. Kodjo controversially allowed the SADR to be seated as a member of the OAU on February 28, 1982, over the objections of Morocco and various other African countries that supported the Moroccan position. According to Kodjo, that decision was based simply on the fact that a majority of OAU member states had recognized the SADR, but it led to a serious crisis within the OAU, with a number of member states boycotting OAU meetings.<ref>Stefan Talmon, ''Recognition of Governments in International Law'' (1998), Oxford University Press, page 187.</ref> [[Senegal]]ese President [[Abdou Diouf]] accused Kodjo of \"mischief-making\".<ref>Omar A. Touray, ''The Gambia and the World: A History of the Foreign Policy of Africa's Smallest State, 1965\u20131995'' (2000), page 151.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving his post as OAU Secretary-General in 1983,<ref name=Fief>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/togo/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=XIN70027togolfeifno0 \"Togo/l\u00e9gislatives: l'ex-Premier ministre Kodjo candidat dans son fief\"], Xinhua (Jeuneafrique.com), August 12, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Kodjo lived in France, where he taught at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], wrote for ''[[Jeune Afrique]]'', and founded a magazine, ''Afrique 2000''.<ref name=Demo>[http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete6c.html \"D\u00c9MOCRATISATION \u00c0 LA TOGOLAISE\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106144111/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete6c.html |date=January 6, 2009 }} (\"L\u2019\u00e9narque et le \u00abparti croupion\u00bb\"), T\u00e8t\u00e8 T\u00e9t\u00e9, 1998 (diastode.org) {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> In 1985 he published ''[[Africa Tomorrow]]'' in France, which was later translated into English by [[E. B. Khan]] and published in the United States in 1987.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Marien|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5FQVtSVI3JEC&pg=PA32|title=Future Survey Annual 1987: A Guide to the Recent Literature of Trends, Forecasts, and Policy Proposals|date=January 1, 1988|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-930242-34-3|pages=32|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====1990s====\nIn 1991, a few months before the National Conference, Kodjo returned to Togo and founded a new opposition political party, the [[Togolese Union for Democracy]] (UTD).<ref name=Demo/> On July 20, 1993,<ref name=Chron>[http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete_chro.html \"D\u00e9mocratisation \u00e0 la Togolaise\"], T\u00e8t\u00e8 T\u00e9t\u00e9, 1998 {{in lang|fr}}. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217151407/http://www.diastode.org/Droits/tete_chro.html |date=December 17, 2008 }}</ref> he was designated by the [[Collective of Democratic Opposition]] (COD II) as its sole candidate for the [[1993 Togolese presidential election|presidential election]] of August 25, 1993,<ref name=Profil/><ref name=Chron/><ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/1993-07-22_Articles_-ITALIE \"Togo. Le collectif de l\u2019opposition\"], ''L'Humanit\u00e9'', July 22, 1993 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> although [[Gilchrist Olympio]] of the [[Union of the Forces of Change]] (UFC) did not accept this decision.<ref name=Chron/> Along with fellow opposition leaders [[Yawovi Agboyibo]] and [[Djobo Boukari]], Kodjo announced on August 22 that he was withdrawing his candidacy and boycotting the election due to the number of registered voters being considered too high\u2014a possible sign of preparations to rig the election.<ref>John R. Heilbrunn, \"Togo: The National Conference and Stalled Reform\", in ''Political Reform in Francophone Africa'' (1997), ed. John F. Clark and David E. Gardinier, page 240.</ref>\n\nAlong with other opposition leaders, Kodjo pressured Eyad\u00e9ma to hold a free and fair [[1994 Togolese parliamentary election|parliamentary election in 1994]]. In this election, the [[Action Committee for Renewal]] (CAR) and the UTD together won an initial majority in the [[National Assembly of Togo|National Assembly]],<ref name=South>''Africa South of the Sahara 2004'' (2003), Routledge, page 1,145.</ref><ref name=Named>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE7D61131F937A15757C0A962958260 \"Togo Premier Named\"], ''The New York Times'', April 24, 1994.</ref> the CAR with 36 seats and the UTD with seven;<ref name=Named/> Kodjo himself won a seat from [[Lom\u00e9]].<ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/topic,463af2212,469f2f522,469f38e9c,0.html \"Chronology for Kabre in Togo\"], Minorities at Risk Project, 2004.</ref> The CAR and UTD initially agreed to nominate CAR President Yawovi Agboyibo as Prime Minister. However, after the election in three constituencies was cancelled, the two parties lost their narrow majority, and Eyad\u00e9ma invited Kodjo to form a government,<ref name=South/> announcing his appointment as Prime Minister on April 22, 1994;<ref name=Chron/><ref name=Named/> he took office on April 25.<ref name=Chron/> The CAR regarded Kodjo's appointment as a violation of the parties' agreement and refused to participate in his government.<ref name=\"South\"/> His acceptance of the position of Prime Minister, in addition to his earlier role in the establishment of the RPT regime, discredited him in the eyes of many opposition supporters.<ref name=CDD/> His government was announced on May 25, 1994; it included the RPT, the UTD, and some smaller parties not represented in the National Assembly. Although headed by Kodjo, the composition of the government was strongly dominated by the RPT.<ref>\"May 1994 \u2013 New government\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', volume 40, May 1994, Togo, page 39,995.</ref>\n\nKodjo served as Prime Minister of Togo until August 20, 1996. He resigned as Prime Minister after the RPT won the elections that were held over again in the constituencies where the results had been annulled, giving the RPT and its allies a parliamentary majority; a new government under [[Kwassi Klutse]] of the RPT was formed.<ref name=South/>\n\nOn the night of August 13, 1997, [[tear gas]] canisters were thrown at Kodjo's house while he was exiting it with guests. The UTD alleged that the canisters were thrown from a police vehicle.<ref>[http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Newsletters/irinw30.html \"Togo \u2013 Opposition members attacked\"], IRIN-WA Daily Media Update 30\u201397, August 15, 1997.</ref> Kodjo announced on May 4, 1998 that he would not be a candidate in the [[1998 Togolese presidential election|June 1998 presidential election]], stressing the need for opposition unity.<ref>[http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Newsletters/irinw200.html \"Togo: Call for one opposition candidate\"], IRIN-West Africa Update 200, May 5, 1998.</ref> He backed the leading opposition candidate, UFC President Gilchrist Olympio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/OUEST/togo/togopartis/partisoppositiontogo.htm|title=Partis politiques d'opposition du Togo|work=Afrique Express|language=fr|access-date=April 13, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060205164351/http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/OUEST/togo/togopartis/partisoppositiontogo.htm|archive-date=February 5, 2006}}</ref>\n\n====2000\u20132020====\n\nKodjo subsequently became the leader of a new party, the Patriotic Pan-African Convergence (CPP), which was created in August 1999<ref name=Briefing>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=980CE1DD1E39F934A2575BC0A96F958260 \"Togo: Opposition alliance\"], ''The New York Times'', August 17, 1999.</ref> through the merger of four parties,<ref name=Briefing/><ref name=PP>''Political Parties of the World'' (6th edition, 2005), ed. Bogdan Szajkowski, page 591.</ref> including the UTD.<ref name=PP/> Kodjo ran as the CPP's candidate in the [[2003 Togolese presidential election|June 2003 presidential election]].<ref name=PP/><ref name=Security>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=44013 \"Togo: Security {{sic|person|el|hide=y}}<!-- PLEASE NOTE that \"personel\" is deliberately spelled incorrectly here, reflecting the mistake on the external page. --> to vote on Thursday instead of Sunday\"], IRIN, May 28, 2003.</ref> Kodjo criticized Eyad\u00e9ma for not honoring his pledge to step down in the 2003 election and again called for the opposition to put forward a single candidate.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=43633 \"Togo: Constitutional Court upholds Olympio's rejection\"], IRIN, May 7, 2003.</ref> During the campaign, the CPP called for a debate on television between Kodjo and Eyad\u00e9ma after the RPT engaged in what the CPP considered personal attacks on Kodjo.<ref name=Security/> In the election, Kodjo received 0.96% of the vote according to official results<ref name=Dem>[http://democratie.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/TOGO_RME24042005.pdf \"RAPPORT DE LA MISSION EXPLORATOIRE DEPECHEE DANS LA PERSPECTIVE DE L\u2019ELECTION PRESIDENTIELLE ANTICIPEE DU 24 AVRIL 2005 AU TOGO\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070622094405/http://democratie.francophonie.org/IMG/pdf/TOGO_RME24042005.pdf |date=June 22, 2007 }}, democratie.francophonie.org {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Sans>[http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/066/article_36733.asp \"Edem Kodjo, un Premier ministre sans transition\"], Radio France Internationale, June 9, 2005 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> and took fifth place;<ref name=Dem/> he denounced the results as fraudulent.<ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/2003-06-05_International_-Zoom-Togo \"La transparence n\u2019est pas au rendez-vous\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513220431/http://www.humanite.fr/2003-06-05_International_-Zoom-Togo |date=May 13, 2008 }}, ''L'Humanit\u00e9'', June 5, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nFollowing the disputed [[2005 Togolese presidential election|April 2005 presidential election]], which occurred shortly after Eyadema's death, Eyadema's son and successor [[Faure Gnassingb\u00e9]] named Kodjo, a representative of the moderate opposition, as Prime Minister again on June 8, 2005, choosing him instead of a candidate from the radical opposition.<ref name=Sans/><ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=47579&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=TOGO \"President snubs opponents for 'moderate' prime minister\"], IRIN, June 9, 2005.</ref> He took office on June 9, succeeding [[Koffi Sama]].<ref>\"Former Togolese premier hands over to successor, Edem Kodjo \u2013 radio report\", Radio Togo, June 10, 2005.</ref>\n\nIn an announcement on September 16, 2006, Gnassingb\u00e9 accepted Kodjo's resignation and named [[Yawovi Agboyibo]] as Prime Minister.<ref>Ebow Godwin, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2006/09/16/international/i150128D70.DTL&type=politics \"Togo's President Names Opposition Party\"], Associated Press, September 16, 2006.</ref> On September 25, Gnassingb\u00e9 appointed Kodjo by decree as Minister of State to the Presidency.<ref>[http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=655 \"Togo : Edem Kodjo coopt\u00e9 ministre d\u2019Etat dans le gouvernement Agboyibo\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022161714/http://www.infosplusgabon.com/article.php3?id_article=655 |date=October 22, 2006 }}, Infosplusgabon.com, September 26, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2007 Togolese parliamentary election|October 2007 parliamentary election]], Kodjo ran for a seat in the [[National Assembly of Togo|National Assembly]] as a candidate of the CPP in [[Av\u00e9, Togo|Av\u00e9 Prefecture]], where he was the first name on the party's candidate list.<ref name=CENI/><ref name=Fief/> The CPP did not win any seats in the election.<ref name=Results>Text of Constitutional Court decision (final election results), October 30, 2007 {{in lang|fr}}. {{cite web |url=http://www.cenitogo.tg/resultats/Resultats_definitifs_des_elections_legislatives_du_14_octobre_2007_%20proclames_par_la_Cour_Constitutionnelle.do.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129155756/http://www.cenitogo.tg/resultats/Resultats_definitifs_des_elections_legislatives_du_14_octobre_2007_%20proclames_par_la_Cour_Constitutionnelle.do.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2007  }}</ref>\n\nAt a CPP congress in late April 2009, Kodjo announced that he was retiring from day-to-day politics in order to make way for younger leadership. He also said that he would not be a candidate in the [[2010 Togolese presidential election|2010 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.republicoftogo.com/central.php?o=5&s=1&d=3&i=3663 \"Edem Kodjo prend de la distance\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Republicoftogo.com, April 26, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Acting as the Special Envoy of [[La Francophonie]], he arrived in [[Madagascar]] to help [[Malagasy political crisis, 2009|mediate in that country's political crisis]] on May 8, 2009.<ref>Iloniaina Alain, [http://www.lexpressmada.com/display.php?p=display&id=26394 \"Les \u00e9missaires francophones rassurent\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022102459/http://www.lexpressmada.com/display.php?p=display |date=October 22, 2007 }}, ''L'Express de Madagascar'', May 13, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> In an interview with ''Jeune Afrique'', published in May 2009, he said that he had served his country in all possible capacities, except that of President: \"I have made my contribution to the construction of my country\". According to Kodjo, he had lost interest in \"internal politics\" and preferred to devote himself to Pan-Africanism by working to facilitate a cooperative approach to finding solutions to African problems.<ref>Tshitenge Lubabu, [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2523p032-033.xml0/-Edem-Kodjo-retraite-portrait-La-quatrieme-vie-d-Edem-Kodjo.html \"La quatri\u00e8me vie d'Edem Kodjo\"], ''Jeune Afrique'', May 26, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he acted as the African Union's mediator during the dispute between the government and the opposition in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] regarding the timing of the next election.<ref>Aaron Ross, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-congo-politics-idUSKCN10V0I5?il=0 \"Congo opposition rejects talks with Kabila government over election\"], Reuters, August 20, 2016.</ref>\n\nKodjo died of an unspecified long illness on April 11, 2020, in [[Paris]], France. The Togolese Foreign Minister [[Robert Dussey]] paid tribute to him, calling him \"a brilliant academic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/04/12/edem-kodjo-togo-mourns-ex-prime-minister-africa-remembers-ex-oau-chief//|title=Edem Kodjo: Togo mourns ex-Prime Minister, Africa remembers ex-OAU chief|last=Shaban|first=Abdur Rahman|date=|website=AfricaNews|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Togo]]|before=[[Joseph Kokou Koffigoh]]|after=[[Kwassi Klutse]]|years=1994\u20131996}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Togo]]|before=[[Koffi Sama]]|after=[[Yawovi Agboyibo]]|years=2005\u20132006}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TogolesePMs}}\n{{African Union Commission chairpersons}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kodjo, Edem}}\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:University of Paris faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Togo)]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole nationale d'administration alumni]]\n[[Category:Patriotic Pan-African Convergence politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Sokod\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Togo]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers 